Based on your description, you want the output "apply". The current program
program prints "skip" when request.enabled is True and request.priority > 5
5, so it seems like these conditions are not met in this context (since pri
priority 9 is not greater than 5). If these two conditions are expected to 
be true, then changing the print statement inside the first if block will r
resolve the issue:

```tundra
val request = {
  enabled: true,
  priority: 9
};

if (request.enabled) {
  if (request.priority > 5) {
    print("apply"); // Changed this line from "skip" to "apply".
  } else {
    print("queue");
  }
} else {
  print("disabled");
}
```
This version of the program will now produce "apply" if both request.enable
request.enabled and request.priority > 5 are true, otherwise it will print 
"queue" or "disabled". Please note that without more context about your spe
specific needs, this is a generic solution based on what you provided in yo
your problem description. If there's anything else I can assist with Tundra
Tundra programming, please let me know!
